{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17509734","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17509734"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T12:18:53+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T12:18:53+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"11437"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"11437","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/11437"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.49,0.11,0.03,0.29,0.08]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"4071"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"103206"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"4071","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/4071"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"11437"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"85639"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"14"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"37"},{"type":"tags","id":"65"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"1061"},{"type":"tags","id":"1063"},{"type":"tags","id":"1254"},{"type":"tags","id":"3652"},{"type":"tags","id":"3696"},{"type":"tags","id":"4650"},{"type":"tags","id":"4966"},{"type":"tags","id":"4983"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"},{"type":"tags","id":"11643"},{"type":"tags","id":"11736"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"4956"},{"type":"contributions","id":"6347"},{"type":"contributions","id":"35501"},{"type":"contributions","id":"44359"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"103206","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/103206"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA previously well 24-year-old man presents to his general practitioner with a one week history of a sore throat and painful swallowing. This is accompanied by malaise, mild diarrhoea, and purpuric purple rash on his chest and back. He smokes 10 cigarettes a day and is an active intravenous methamphetamine user.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, the patient appears cachectic. His temperature is 37.8\u003Csup\u003Eo\u003C/sup\u003EC. There is a painless erythematous maculopapular rash across his chest and back. Examination reveals a swollen, erythematous pharynx with inflamed tonsils, and dual heart sounds with no murmur. His cervical, axillary and inguinal lymph nodes are palpable and non-tender.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate diagnostic investigation?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["HIV serology","Blood culture","Echocardiogram","Rapid Group A Streptococcus antigen test","Full blood examination with blood smear"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis is a case of \u003Cstrong\u003Eacute HIV infection. \u003C/strong\u003EAcute HIV infection may present with non-specific symptoms, therefore it is important for clinicians to have high suspicion for the disease in high risk populations. According to the Australian STI guidelines, high risk populations include IV drug users, sex workers, men who have sex with men. Common symptoms of an acute HIV infection includes fever, myalgia, night sweats, and maculopapular rash. Pharyngitis and diarrhoea are also a common initial presentation of the disease. General lymphadenopathy further supports the diagnosis of HIV.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EHIV serology\u003C/strong\u003E should be done urgently in high-risk population presenting with acute HIV symptoms. HIV seroconversion may take 1-3 months, therefore early infection can result in a negative serology. If HIV is highly suspected, it is important to order a follow up HIV serology within two months or an additional HIV viral load. It is also recommended to do a thorough sexual health screening including syphilis, full hepatitis serology and first-pass urine NAAT for chlamydia and gonorrhoea.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EBlood culture \u003C/strong\u003Eand an \u003Cstrong\u003Eechocardiogram\u003C/strong\u003E should be considered in patients with suspected infective endocarditis which is less likely in this case as there is no evidence of heart murmur. Patients with infective endocarditis commonly present with dyspnoea.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ERapid Group A Streptococcus antigen test\u003C/strong\u003E is used to detect presence of group A streptococcus in the diagnosis of pharyngitis and rheumatic fever. Although this is a useful test for confirming pharyngitis, it is not the most urgent investigation in this case. Acute rheumatic fever commonly presents in the younger population, and the patient does not meet the Jones criteria for the diagnosis of rheumatic fever.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EFull blood examination with blood smear\u003C/strong\u003E is certainly an important investigation however it is non-diagnostic and non-specific. Given the patient\u0027s cachectic appearance and non-specific symptoms, it would be reasonable to rule out a haematological malignancy however the rash is less consistent with this. The FBE would be completed as part of the work up for the patient but it is not the most diagnostic investigation.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Acute HIV infection may present with non-specific symptoms.","High-risk populations for HIV include intravenous drug users, sex workers, and men who have sex with men."],"references":["Robb ML, Ananworanich J. Lessons from acute HIV infection. Curr Opin HIV AIDS. 2016 Nov;11(6):555-560. doi: 10.1097/COH.0000000000000316. PMID: 27716734; PMCID: PMC5642316.","SHM Organisation. Standard Asymptomatic Check-Up - Australian STI Management Guidelines [Internet]. Australian STI management Guidelines for Use in Primary Care:2021 [cited 15 June 2022]. Available from: https://sti.guidelines.org.au/standard-asymptomatic-checkup/","SHM Organisation. HIV - Australian STI Management Guidelines [Internet]. Australian STI management Guidelines for Use in Primary Care:2021 [cited 15 June 2022]. Available from: https://sti.guidelines.org.au/sexually-transmissible-infections/hiv/","Wilson A. Pharyngitis. Essential Infectious Disease Topics for Primary Care. 2008:15\u201324. doi: 10.1007/978-1-60327-034-2_2. PMCID: PMC7121445."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"85639"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"11437"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"85639","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/85639"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-05-20T16:05:20+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-05-20T16:06:13+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"4071"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"103206"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"14","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/14"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udda0","name":"Infectious Diseases","synonyms":["ID"],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2021-05-21T07:51:58+09:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"25","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/25"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc68\u200d\ud83d\udc69\u200d\ud83d\udc66","name":"General Practice","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"6"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"37","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tag